 across a diverse range of media forms, including screen media (film, television and online video), newspapers, memoirs, music festivals and social media platforms (notably Facebook, YouTube and Flickr). Examining the historical, cultural and political contexts that have shaped the mediation of humanitarian relationships since the middle of the twentieth century, the book reveals significant synergies between the humanitarian enterprise - the endeavour to alleviate the suffering of particular groups - and its media representations, particularly in their modes of addressing and appealing to specific publics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCrises in mass media. 0aHumanitarian assistance. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aCampaigns.  aEmergency.  aGlobal humanitarianism.  aHistory.  aMedia culture.  aMedia representations.  aPolitics.  aPopular Culture.  aintervention.  anon Governmental Organisations.1 aAndrade, Gabriel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauman, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaudhuri, Shohini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristiansen, Lene Bull, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFricker, Toby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawrence, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawrence, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLoukopoulou, Katerina, econtributor.4ctb4ht